Data from Grab et al. (2020): https://doi.org/10.3929/ethz-b-000434697,
which makes use of SwissTopo data.

How the example data in this folder was obtained and processed
=============================================================

1) Download the source GeoTIFF files
------------------------------------

From the ETH research collection release, download:

- https://www.research-collection.ethz.ch/bitstream/handle/20.500.11850/434697/08_SurfaceElevation_SGI.zip
- https://www.research-collection.ethz.ch/bitstream/handle/20.500.11850/434697/04_IceThickness_SGI.zip

Example commands:

```sh
wget https://www.research-collection.ethz.ch/bitstream/handle/20.500.11850/434697/08_SurfaceElevation_SGI.zip
wget https://www.research-collection.ethz.ch/bitstream/handle/20.500.11850/434697/04_IceThickness_SGI.zip
```

2) Extract the specific glacier tiles
-------------------------------------

```sh
unzip 04_IceThickness_SGI.zip 04_IceThickness_SGI/A54g-11_IceThickness.tif
unzip 08_SurfaceElevation_SGI.zip 08_SurfaceElevation_SGI/A54g-11_SwissALTI3D_r2019.tif
```

3) Load and clean in Julia
--------------------------

Install and use `Rasters.jl` to read GeoTIFFs. Replace nodata values (`-9999`) with `NaN`.

```julia
using Rasters

surface = Raster("08_SurfaceElevation_SGI/A54g-11_SwissALTI3D_r2019.tif")
thick = Raster("04_IceThickness_SGI/A54g-11_IceThickness.tif")

surface[surface .== -9999] .= NaN
thick[thick .== -9999] .= NaN
```

4) Compute bed elevation
------------------------

```julia
bed = surface - thick
```

5) Downsample and extract arrays
--------------------------------

The data was thinned by a factor of 2 in each direction.

```julia
thin = 2
x = collect(surface.dims[1].val.data)[1:thin:end]
y = collect(surface.dims[2].val.data)[1:thin:end]
bed_arr = bed.data[1:thin:end, 1:thin:end, 1]
surface_arr = surface.data[1:thin:end, 1:thin:end, 1]
```

6) Write binary files used by examples
--------------------------------------

```julia
open("data/bed.bin", "w") do f
    write(f, Float32.(bed_arr))
end
open("data/surface.bin", "w") do f
    write(f, Float32.(surface_arr))
end
open("data/x.bin", "w") do f
    write(f, Float32.(x))
end
open("data/y.bin", "w") do f
    write(f, Float32.(y))
end
```
